<h1>Daniel Lemire</h1>

<div>
<img style="border: 1px solid black; margin: 5px; float: right; width: 125px;" src="http://www.daniel-lemire.com/fr/images/JPG/profile2008.jpg" alt="Daniel Lemire's picture" />
</div>

<p>I have two sons: <a
href="http://www.daniel-lemire.com/lohan/">Lohan</a> and <a
href="http://www.daniel-lemire.com/louka/">Louka</a>.</p>

<p>
Professor,  <a href="http://www.professeurs.uqam.ca/pages/lemire.daniel.htm"
">UQAM</a><br />
Adjunct Professor, <a href="http://www.unb.ca"
rel="nofollow">University of New Brunswick</a>
</p>

<p >As a researcher, I'm interested in Multidimensional Databases
(<a href="http://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/OLAP"><abbr
title="On-Line Analytical Processing">OLAP</abbr></a>), Data Mining 
over Text and Time Series and <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collaborative_filtering">Collaborative
Filtering</a> (see <a
href="http://www.indiscover.net">inDiscover</a>).</p>

<p>I am currently a tenured professor at the <a
href="http://www.uqam.ca/" rel="nofollow">University of Quebec at
Montreal</a> where I teach Computer Science. Prior to joining the
University of Quebec, I was a researcher in the Internet Logic
group at <abbr
title="National Research Council of Canada">NRC</abbr> and the
group leader of the e-Health Research Group. Before joining NRC,
I was a professor at <a href="http://www.acadiau.ca"
rel="nofollow">Acadia University</a>, an industry consultant, and
an NSERC postdoctoral fellow at the <em>Institut de génie
biomédical</em>. During my days in industry, I designed the <a
href="http://www.waaves.com/">Waaves format</a> for the National
Radiology Server (in France) and Signal Processing software for
the geophysical industry&mdash;see the <a href="http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-4750490412418990197">video on Google Video</a>. I earned my Ph.D. from the École
Polytechnique de Montréal and graduated from the <a
href="http://www.toronto.edu/" rel="nofollow">University of
Toronto</a>.</p>

<ul>
<li>In 2007, with Kamel Aouiche, I surveyed <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/cs.DB/0703058">probabilistic view-size
estimation algorithms</a> and showed that Adaptive Counting was the most scalable technique to date.</li>


<li>In  2006, I showed that we can compute the <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/cs.DS/0610046">running maximum-minimum using three&nbsp;comparisons or less per element</a>. The algorithm is simple and practical.</li>

<li>In 2005, with Anna Maclachlan, I designed the rating-based collaborative filtering
algorithm  <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Slope One</span> now used in
several software libraries such as <a href="http://taste.sourceforge.net/">Taste</a> 
and <a href="http://www.vogoo-api.com/">Vogoo</a>, in several
Web sites (<a href="http://www.indiscover.net">inDiscover</a>, 
<a href="http://www.hitflip.de">hitflip</a>) and Web tools
(<a href="http://www.drupal.org/project/cre">Drupal</a>).</li>

<li>In 2002, I won the <a
href="http://www.daniel-lemire.com/fr/abstracts/CASCON2002.html">Best
Paper</a> Award at the <a
href="https://www-927.ibm.com/ibm/cas/archives/2002/papers/index.shtml">
CASCON conference</a> organized by IBM for my work on <abbr
title="On-Line Analytical Processing">OLAP</abbr>.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Collaborative Data Management, Database Theory, Bitmap Indexes, Data Warehousing, Multidimensional
Databases (OLAP), Data Mining, Time Series, Collaborative Filtering, Information Retrieval. - <a
href="http://www.daniel-lemire.com/fr/documents/CV/CVdeDanielLemire_ENGLISH.pdf"
 rel="nofollow">c.v.</a> (pdf) </p>


